G\u003C/strong\u003E is the only immunoglobulin class that crosses the placenta. This occurs through active transport mediated by neonatal Fc receptors expressed on placental cells. This selective transfer process ensures passive immunity is provided to the developing fetus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgA\u003C/strong\u003E is secreted into mucous membranes and provides mucosal immunity but does not cross the placental barrier. \u003Cstrong\u003EIgM\u003C/strong\u003E molecules are pentameric and too large to cross the placental barrier. \u003Cstrong\u003EIgD\u003C/strong\u003E primarily functions as an antigen receptor on B lymphocytes and cannot traverse the placenta. \u003Cstrong\u003EIgE\u003C/strong\u003E mediates allergic responses and immunity against parasitic infections but lacks the ability to cross the placental barrier.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe transferred maternal IgG antibodies protect the newborn for 3-6 months after birth, providing crucial immunity while the infant\u0027s own immune system develops.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["IgG is the only immunoglobulin class that crosses the placenta, providing passive immunity to the developing fetus","Placental transfer of IgG occurs via active transport using neonatal Fc receptors","Maternal IgG provides protection for the newborn during the first 3-6 months of life"],"references":["Palmeira P, Quinello C, Silveira-Lessa AL, Zago CA, Carneiro-Sampaio M. IgG placental transfer in healthy and pathological pregnancies. Clin Dev Immunol. 2012;2012:985646. doi: 10.1155/2012/985646. Epub 2011 Oct 1. PMID: 22235228; PMCID: PMC3251916.","Bona, C. A., \u0026 Bonilla, F. A. (2019). Textbook of immunology. CRC press","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97430"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14977"}